{"cursor":"7597","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n:Not to be confused with a [[Fixed point (mathematics)|fixed point]] where\nx=f(x). s (blue squares). The stationary points in this graph are all relative\nmaxima or relative minima.]] In mathematics, particularly in calculus, a\n'stationary point' is an input to a function where the derivative is zero\n(equivalently, the slope is zero): where the function \"stops\" increasing or\ndecreasing (hence the name).\n\nFor the graph of a one-dimensional function, this corresponds to a point on the\ngraph where the tangent is parallel to the x-axis. For the graph of a two-\ndimensional function, this corresponds to a point on the graph where the tangent\nplane is parallel to the xy plane.\n\nThe term is mostly used in two dimensions, which this article discusses:\nstationary points in higher dimensions are usually referred to as critical\npoints; see there for higher dimensional discussion.\n","linknr":150,"url":"Stationary_point","recorded":1362671455,"links":25,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","geometry","mathematics","stationary_points"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Differential calculus"],"headings":["Stationary points, critical points and turning points","Classification","Curve sketching","See also","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Stationary_vs_inflection_pts.svg/350px-Stationary_vs_inflection_pts.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/d/8/cd81d846781f418f883642fab802ae4a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/d/d/1dd01664b6156e48d862df5ce454cfa3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/9/1/491bd7679787ca96745ecb9f6d79534a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/10/Stationary_and_inflection_pts.gif","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Cubic_graph_special_points.svg/272px-Cubic_graph